1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:15,950 --> 00:00:18,950
Don't pee on it. Don't worry.

3
00:00:21,040 --> 00:00:21,980
I still don't get it.

4
00:00:21,980 --> 00:00:22,340
Why.

5
00:00:27,450 --> 00:00:28,550
Why a painting?

6
00:00:29,150 --> 00:00:31,550
Don't you want to give her something practical for the wedding?

7
00:00:31,950 --> 00:00:32,850
Like a blender.

8
00:00:33,150 --> 00:00:34,650
Ziza and a blender?

9
00:00:35,250 --> 00:00:36,450
She has teeth again.

10
00:00:37,250 --> 00:00:38,050
Or a vase.

11
00:00:39,050 --> 00:00:41,600
You know, a big jug without a handle.

12
00:00:41,950 --> 00:00:43,280
I know what a vase is.

13
00:00:43,550 --> 00:00:46,420
Why would I give that to Ziza?

14
00:00:46,550 --> 00:00:48,100
Every woman likes flowers.

15
00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:48,260
Yeah.

16
00:00:48,950 --> 00:00:50,850
And what's she going to do with a vase?

17
00:00:51,420 --> 00:00:52,340
Well, nothing then.

18
00:00:56,050 --> 00:00:57,350
It's a nice piece of work anyway.

19
00:00:58,250 --> 00:00:59,280
And it's named like a pub.

20
00:00:59,280 --> 00:00:59,820
What?

21
00:01:00,850 --> 00:01:01,950
Still life.

22
00:01:02,750 --> 00:01:04,650
I just don't know what to call this still life.

23
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:06,400
Beer?

24
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:10,740
Nice one, bro!

25
00:01:13,150 --> 00:01:15,950
Hold on, something's happened.

26
00:01:27,350 --> 00:01:29,150
I could already feel something had happened.

27
00:01:40,270 --> 00:01:41,410
They said there's enough water?

28
00:01:42,210 --> 00:01:42,530
Yeah.

29
00:01:48,650 --> 00:01:54,770
What's going on?

30
00:01:54,770 --> 00:02:29,200
They're terrible, not people.

31
00:02:29,420 --> 00:02:31,600
Look who's talking, what got into you?

32
00:02:31,950 --> 00:02:32,430
Into me?

33
00:02:32,650 --> 00:02:33,770
Into Roubal, wasn't it?

34
00:02:33,970 --> 00:02:34,830
You started it.

35
00:02:34,910 --> 00:02:36,730
But he was already filling his second bucket of water.

36
00:02:37,690 --> 00:02:38,090
Here.

37
00:02:40,750 --> 00:02:41,550
What's this?

38
00:02:42,150 --> 00:02:43,320
Sorry, bro, it was a battle.

39
00:02:43,320 --> 00:02:44,060
I'll buy you a new one.

40
00:02:44,460 --> 00:02:44,860
Oh.

41
00:02:45,950 --> 00:02:47,750
And I have this one half-painted.

42
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:48,800
Great.

43
00:02:48,860 --> 00:02:49,820
Now that matters to you.

44
00:02:49,820 --> 00:02:52,460
But grabbing a bucket and coming with us to get water, that's a no.

45
00:02:52,460 --> 00:02:53,280
For water?

46
00:02:54,150 --> 00:02:55,580
What if someone saw me there?

47
00:02:55,850 --> 00:02:56,850
No, that's great.

48
00:02:57,350 --> 00:02:58,000
Calm down.

49
00:02:58,000 --> 00:02:59,560
We'll go when things settle down a bit.

50
00:02:59,880 --> 00:03:01,280
They said there's plenty of water.

51
00:03:01,480 --> 00:03:01,600
Right.

52
00:03:02,050 --> 00:03:05,650
Exactly, when they announce there's plenty of something, that means there isn't.

53
00:03:05,650 --> 00:03:06,850
Why do you think they announce it?

54
00:03:07,770 --> 00:03:08,130
Propaganda.

55
00:03:09,010 --> 00:03:11,030
We're living in 2010, aren't we?

56
00:03:11,490 --> 00:03:12,710
Ivuska, it's always the same.

57
00:03:13,050 --> 00:03:14,910
The Russians turn off the tap and we get nothing.

58
00:03:15,130 --> 00:03:16,750
We don't get our water from the Russians.

59
00:03:16,870 --> 00:03:18,710
From the French then, big difference.

60
00:03:19,150 --> 00:03:21,150
You're talking nonsense and I'm without my jug.

61
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:23,090
You mean without your jug?

62
00:03:23,250 --> 00:03:24,850
Of course, without it I'm done for.

63
00:03:25,650 --> 00:03:33,600
Ozzak, the fact that you don't have a jug and the general water shortage are two incomparably different problems.

64
00:03:33,600 --> 00:03:34,720
Then explain that to me.

65
00:03:35,420 --> 00:03:37,280
Couldn't you just imagine the jug?

66
00:03:37,440 --> 00:03:38,980
I could, and you can imagine the water.

67
00:03:40,250 --> 00:03:47,240
Ozzak, you imagining a jug and the two of us imagining water is an incomparably big difference.

68
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:49,940
Well yeah, because I'd be imagining something useful.

69
00:03:50,160 --> 00:03:51,400
And water isn't useful?

70
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:51,920
Well, it is.

71
00:03:52,450 --> 00:03:54,650
Uncle, you can't do anything without water.

72
00:03:54,650 --> 00:03:55,930
Cook, do laundry, clean.

73
00:03:56,070 --> 00:03:56,490
Me?

74
00:03:57,650 --> 00:03:58,610
Well, more like me.

75
00:03:58,950 --> 00:03:59,850
And does that bother you?

76
00:04:00,250 --> 00:04:01,450
And we also have to wash.

77
00:04:01,450 --> 00:04:01,790
Why?

78
00:04:02,130 --> 00:04:03,410
So we don't stink.

79
00:04:03,590 --> 00:04:04,210
And do you stink?

80
00:04:04,850 --> 00:04:06,410
No, but without water we will.

81
00:04:06,410 --> 00:04:07,590
Well, I feel sorry for you then.

82
00:04:10,050 --> 00:04:10,650
Damn it, forget it, I'm going.

83
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:11,720
Where?

84
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:12,820
To Krivonka's.

85
00:04:12,900 --> 00:04:15,500
Wait, you won't even help us when the next tanker comes?

86
00:04:15,660 --> 00:04:15,820
No.

87
00:04:15,960 --> 00:04:17,280
But you can imagine it.

88
00:04:39,450 --> 00:04:40,950
I'm calling those French people.

89
00:04:43,050 --> 00:04:43,750
What?

90
00:04:45,330 --> 00:04:46,430
Can I speak Czech?

91
00:04:46,910 --> 00:04:47,430
I see.

92
00:04:47,690 --> 00:04:48,530
Well, okay then.

93
00:04:48,530 --> 00:04:53,090
I wanted to ask if there's enough water.

94
00:04:53,090 --> 00:04:53,610
There is.

95
00:04:53,750 --> 00:04:54,910
Then why isn't there any here?

96
00:04:54,950 --> 00:04:55,850
The tanker is empty.

97
00:04:57,650 --> 00:04:59,010
Right, they're working on it.

98
00:04:59,150 --> 00:05:02,350
Okay, and roughly when can we expect it?

99
00:05:02,950 --> 00:05:03,650
Right now?

100
00:05:04,350 --> 00:05:05,650
Wonderful, thank you.

101
00:05:05,950 --> 00:05:08,450
And au revoir.

102
00:05:09,350 --> 00:05:10,650
Oui, oui.

103
00:05:11,980 --> 00:05:12,600
So what?

104
00:05:14,350 --> 00:05:16,250
She complimented my French.

105
00:05:16,600 --> 00:05:17,740
What about the tanker?

106
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:19,640
They're working on it.

107
00:05:20,450 --> 00:05:24,450
Didn't you tell me the other day that when they say they're working on something, it means it'll never happen?

108
00:05:24,710 --> 00:05:25,450
Propaganda again.

109
00:05:25,970 --> 00:05:26,910
I hope not.

110
00:05:27,030 --> 00:05:27,970
I need to wash my hair.

111
00:05:28,190 --> 00:05:29,690
Hold on, that can wait, can't it?

112
00:05:30,050 --> 00:05:32,350
There's school photos tomorrow, I'm not going there looking like a mess.

113
00:05:32,950 --> 00:05:34,050
Or should I go to the hairdresser?

114
00:05:34,350 --> 00:05:39,250
Hairdressers are only there to take money from you for something you can do yourself.

115
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:41,150
Isn't that propaganda?

116
00:05:42,660 --> 00:05:43,160
Right.

117
00:05:43,420 --> 00:05:43,920
Bye.

118
00:05:44,850 --> 00:05:45,360
Hi.

119
00:05:45,750 --> 00:05:47,580
How come I didn't see you at the tanker?

120
00:05:47,950 --> 00:05:49,050
What tanker?

121
00:05:49,450 --> 00:05:51,300
Downstairs in front of the building, the water's out.

122
00:05:51,450 --> 00:05:52,640
Oh, we didn't know.

123
00:05:53,150 --> 00:05:55,150
We're only allowed to use water on Thursdays.

124
00:05:55,550 --> 00:05:58,450
Mom says wasting water kills walruses.

125
00:05:59,250 --> 00:06:00,450
Why walruses?

126
00:06:00,700 --> 00:06:04,020
Because they need water, so less water means fewer walruses.

127
00:06:04,120 --> 00:06:05,680
And I love walruses.

128
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:07,440
I hate walruses.

129
00:06:07,460 --> 00:06:07,960
Lexa!

130
00:06:08,140 --> 00:06:11,700
What, they're everywhere, they poop on statues and spread ticks.

131
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:13,840
Those are pigeons, Lexa.

132
00:06:15,450 --> 00:06:18,370
That boy confuses walruses with pigeons?

133
00:06:18,630 --> 00:06:23,210
In second grade, Lexa cut up his biology textbook into a memory game and then glued it back together wrong.

134
00:06:23,290 --> 00:06:25,470
Since then he confuses birds and pinnipeds.

135
00:06:25,570 --> 00:06:27,430
Sis, you're such a huge lazy butt!

136
00:06:27,550 --> 00:06:28,110
Lexa!

137
00:06:28,340 --> 00:06:29,100
Then don't say stuff like that.

138
00:06:29,180 --> 00:06:30,220
What, isn't it true?

139
00:06:30,460 --> 00:06:31,360
It's total nonsense.

140
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:33,740
Yeah, I'm just a chicken butt then, right?

141
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:36,660
Sorry then.

142
00:06:37,550 --> 00:06:40,760
Ivo, could I borrow your umbrella tomorrow for the photos?

143
00:06:41,050 --> 00:06:41,950
Is it going to rain?

144
00:06:42,350 --> 00:06:45,500
No, but the photographer will want to put me behind Kruta again.

145
00:06:45,950 --> 00:06:48,560
So I wanted to at least hold up an umbrella so people can see where I'm standing.

146
00:06:48,560 --> 00:06:50,060
How about we take a photo together?

147
00:06:50,660 --> 00:06:51,140
Sure.

148
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:52,240
Just the two of us.

149
00:06:53,650 --> 00:06:56,240
I don't know, because of the walruses.

150
00:06:56,240 --> 00:06:57,600
Do you need water for a photo?

151
00:06:59,760 --> 00:07:00,240
Lots of it.

152
00:07:00,250 --> 00:07:03,200
A photo isn't wasting, a photo is a keepsake.

153
00:07:03,650 --> 00:07:07,050
And don't tell me your mom doesn't have at least one photo of you in her wallet.

154
00:07:07,100 --> 00:07:07,580
She doesn't.

155
00:07:07,580 --> 00:07:09,720
But she already has a spot saved for one.

156
00:07:10,050 --> 00:07:12,340
So get your photo taken together and give it to her.

157
00:07:12,650 --> 00:07:16,280
But we can't, we have to wait until we're eighteen to get photos.

158
00:07:16,750 --> 00:07:17,260
Why?

159
00:07:17,650 --> 00:07:20,450
So mom has something to remember us by when we leave home.

160
00:07:21,850 --> 00:07:26,350
I think I'll go check if they've brought another tanker.

161
00:07:26,650 --> 00:07:29,950
I hope people won't act like vultures again.

162
00:07:30,910 --> 00:07:32,390
The one with the swordfish snout.

163
00:07:35,070 --> 00:07:35,690
Vultures, right?

164
00:07:42,650 --> 00:07:43,520
That's heavy.

165
00:07:43,750 --> 00:07:44,650
I don't have another one.

166
00:07:45,550 --> 00:07:47,250
So what am I supposed to do now?

167
00:07:47,850 --> 00:07:49,050
Paint something else.

168
00:07:49,740 --> 00:07:50,540
She already has teeth.

169
00:07:52,550 --> 00:07:55,680
They promised each other engagement teeth instead of rings.

170
00:07:55,750 --> 00:07:57,690
Krakora was always a cheapskate.

171
00:07:57,690 --> 00:07:58,630
Yeah, well.

172
00:07:59,350 --> 00:08:01,240
Ziza sure is a clever girl though.

173
00:08:01,350 --> 00:08:03,560
Landing the best bartender in all of Zizkov?

174
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:05,050
That's a jackpot.

175
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:06,040
He's weird.

176
00:08:06,040 --> 00:08:07,350
I think he waters down the beer.

177
00:08:08,550 --> 00:08:09,450
You're jealous.

178
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:10,680
I'm not jealous!

179
00:08:11,250 --> 00:08:12,350
So what, are you sulking?

180
00:08:13,750 --> 00:08:14,600
She betrayed us.

181
00:08:14,600 --> 00:08:15,080
Who?

182
00:08:15,650 --> 00:08:16,750
Me, Pitl and Metlos.

183
00:08:18,450 --> 00:08:20,820
We once promised each other we'd drink together through thick and thin.

184
00:08:20,820 --> 00:08:22,240
And now she's moving to the country.

185
00:08:22,460 --> 00:08:23,720
So you'll visit her.

186
00:08:23,720 --> 00:08:25,680
That's hard, Krakora is insanely jealous.

187
00:08:26,050 --> 00:08:28,260
She had to promise him she wouldn't drink with her exes.

188
00:08:28,750 --> 00:08:29,950
He hates me the most.

189
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:31,720
Oh dear.

190
00:08:32,750 --> 00:08:34,650
So you were her first, huh?

191
00:08:35,110 --> 00:08:35,490
Yeah.

192
00:08:36,860 --> 00:08:38,180
Her alcohol addiction started with me.

193
00:08:41,450 --> 00:08:42,250
Hello.

194
00:08:43,850 --> 00:08:45,830
Could I stash something here?

195
00:08:45,830 --> 00:08:46,830
Some hot goods?

196
00:08:47,590 --> 00:08:48,430
More like cold.

197
00:08:48,850 --> 00:08:49,650
For how long?

198
00:08:49,850 --> 00:08:50,790
Just briefly.

199
00:08:50,950 --> 00:08:52,110
It's quality merchandise.

200
00:08:53,150 --> 00:08:53,530
In short supply.

201
00:08:53,690 --> 00:08:56,690
You said that about those carp too, and they've been sitting in my tub for two months.

202
00:08:56,870 --> 00:08:58,710
I'm waiting for December, that's when the prices are best.

203
00:08:58,850 --> 00:08:59,970
It's starting to smell a bit.

204
00:09:00,090 --> 00:09:01,330
Fish should be aged, right?

205
00:09:01,970 --> 00:09:02,510
Horvat, you?

206
00:09:03,470 --> 00:09:04,190
Got a jug?

207
00:09:04,330 --> 00:09:04,650
I do.

208
00:09:05,410 --> 00:09:06,050
What's it look like?

209
00:09:06,550 --> 00:09:07,370
Something like this.

210
00:09:07,370 --> 00:09:08,430
But I need a bigger one.

211
00:09:08,430 --> 00:09:10,150
I saw something like that near Old Town Square.

212
00:09:11,450 --> 00:09:12,010
I'll try.

213
00:09:13,420 --> 00:09:14,840
Will you open the elevator for me?

214
00:09:15,020 --> 00:09:15,960
What've you got that's so big?

215
00:09:18,140 --> 00:09:18,700
A tanker.

216
00:09:20,250 --> 00:09:23,550
He wanted to seize it out back while nobody was guarding the cab.

217
00:09:27,100 --> 00:09:28,820
You speak some kind of dialect.

218
00:09:35,350 --> 00:09:38,660
Good thing you stay hydrated and brought that bottle.

219
00:09:38,950 --> 00:09:40,820
Otherwise we wouldn't even have coffee.

220
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:42,000
That's water from Fiji.

221
00:09:43,720 --> 00:09:44,020
Really?

222
00:09:45,550 --> 00:09:49,250
Those French really do control everything, don't they?

223
00:09:50,070 --> 00:09:52,130
Does your water work at home?

224
00:09:52,130 --> 00:09:54,680
No, but our water's never worked.

225
00:09:54,850 --> 00:09:57,150
Zoran doesn't trust the public water supply.

226
00:09:57,950 --> 00:10:00,250
I see, and what water do you use?

227
00:10:01,250 --> 00:10:04,550
Evian for washing, Perrier for drinking.

228
00:10:05,950 --> 00:10:07,350
That's what I call luxury.

229
00:10:08,050 --> 00:10:09,100
I'm not very happy with it.

230
00:10:09,450 --> 00:10:12,080
Zoran buys it in those little 30cl bottles.

231
00:10:12,650 --> 00:10:14,250
Try flushing the toilet with those.

232
00:10:19,800 --> 00:10:20,420
Where are you?

233
00:10:21,050 --> 00:10:21,850
Where do you think?

234
00:10:22,180 --> 00:10:25,640
They brought a tanker and by the time I stood in line, they drove it away again.

235
00:10:25,840 --> 00:10:27,260
And how am I supposed to wash my hair?

236
00:10:27,460 --> 00:10:28,760
They'll probably bring another one.

237
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:29,560
But when?

238
00:10:29,680 --> 00:10:32,640
I can't go to bed with wet hair, when I smooth it down I look like an idiot.

239
00:10:32,860 --> 00:10:33,880
So put it in a ponytail.

240
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:34,820
A ponytail?

241
00:10:35,750 --> 00:10:36,650
For school photos?

242
00:10:36,650 --> 00:10:37,750
Well, sorry.

243
00:10:38,050 --> 00:10:40,580
I'll run to the Vietnamese shop and buy some bottled water.

244
00:10:40,950 --> 00:10:42,050
And wash it right away.

245
00:10:42,900 --> 00:10:45,920
Ivuska, don't buy Magnesia, shampoo doesn't lather in it at all.

246
00:10:46,320 --> 00:10:49,240
Wait, don't be crazy, they'll bring more any minute and it'll be free.

247
00:10:49,950 --> 00:10:52,350
So why doesn't Ivuska go to the hairdresser?

248
00:10:52,750 --> 00:10:54,850
Because they won't bring that for free.

249
00:10:54,850 --> 00:11:00,500
Tomas, school photos are a memory for life.

250
00:11:00,750 --> 00:11:05,600
The last time Iva went to the hairdresser, the bill was also a memory for life.

251
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:08,140
And I only had it washed and blow-dried.

252
00:11:08,850 --> 00:11:12,260
Why should I pay for something you can do yourself for free?

253
00:11:12,260 --> 00:11:15,120
Next time the drain clogs, you can fix it yourself for free.

254
00:11:15,520 --> 00:11:16,540
I'm not a plumber.

255
00:11:16,700 --> 00:11:17,740
I'm not a hairdresser.

256
00:11:17,920 --> 00:11:18,520
Enough.

257
00:11:19,050 --> 00:11:22,360
We'll just wait for the tanker and you'll look great for the photos.

258
00:11:22,360 --> 00:11:24,680
If not, I'll wear a hat.

259
00:11:25,280 --> 00:11:26,840
Are you trying to threaten me?

260
00:11:27,950 --> 00:11:29,650
I think you look nice in a hat.

261
00:11:37,350 --> 00:11:44,370
My father was an insensitive jerk, but he never said anything this terrible to me.

262
00:11:52,750 --> 00:11:53,860
I'm not visible here either.

263
00:11:53,860 --> 00:11:55,570
And not here either.

264
00:11:56,850 --> 00:12:00,150
Yeah, that photographer puts you behind Kruta on purpose.

265
00:12:00,750 --> 00:12:03,550
But once I have an umbrella, everyone will see where I am.

266
00:12:04,950 --> 00:12:06,550
Everyone will see where the umbrella is.

267
00:12:07,050 --> 00:12:07,750
At least that.

268
00:12:08,660 --> 00:12:10,940
If I don't find water by tonight, I'll stand next to you.

269
00:12:11,060 --> 00:12:12,640
We can both fit behind Kruta.

270
00:12:13,100 --> 00:12:13,660
True.

271
00:12:13,660 --> 00:12:17,150
Look, behind her it's me, Voracek and Ruzicka.

272
00:12:17,650 --> 00:12:18,950
Ruzicka is from class C, right?

273
00:12:19,050 --> 00:12:22,650
He came to bury his Tamagotchi behind Voracek.

274
00:12:25,330 --> 00:12:25,770
Hey.

275
00:12:27,540 --> 00:12:28,080
What is it?

276
00:12:29,150 --> 00:12:30,450
Hey, I'll bring you a hat.

277
00:12:31,150 --> 00:12:31,950
Why?

278
00:12:32,550 --> 00:12:34,300
For our group photo, we'll have matching ones.

279
00:12:34,650 --> 00:12:36,850
Forget it, I'm not taking a photo with you.

280
00:12:37,050 --> 00:12:39,580
No, I meant the three of us with sis.

281
00:12:39,850 --> 00:12:41,120
That's happened before.

282
00:12:41,120 --> 00:12:43,440
And didn't we look great in that photo, right, sis?

283
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:48,450
You cut Sasa out and then showed the photo to the boys like we were dating.

284
00:12:49,350 --> 00:12:50,150
No, no.

285
00:12:50,750 --> 00:12:55,250
Lexa, you put it on the bulletin board and wrote "Romeo and Juliet" on it.

286
00:12:55,550 --> 00:12:57,050
We were, you know.

287
00:12:57,750 --> 00:12:58,750
We weren't and we won't be.

288
00:13:00,290 --> 00:13:01,670
Ivo, come on, forgive him.

289
00:13:01,870 --> 00:13:04,010
We don't have any photo together with Lexa.

290
00:13:04,170 --> 00:13:05,450
No, not since he cut you out.

291
00:13:05,670 --> 00:13:06,070
Right.

292
00:13:08,650 --> 00:13:10,650
Fine, but you stand in the middle.

293
00:13:12,250 --> 00:13:14,600
The photographer probably wouldn't let me stand in the middle.

294
00:13:14,850 --> 00:13:15,950
Why wouldn't he?

295
00:13:16,850 --> 00:13:26,350
When we took photos the year before last, I was standing between Kropackova and Machova and he asked them if they could kindly stand closer together so there wouldn't be that weird gap.

296
00:13:27,850 --> 00:13:30,450
If you want the photo, fine.

297
00:13:31,050 --> 00:13:32,550
But I'm not standing next to Lexa.

298
00:13:33,450 --> 00:13:35,110
Fine, I'll stand in the middle.

299
00:13:35,350 --> 00:13:36,250
Sasa will stand next to me.

300
00:13:36,250 --> 00:13:36,930
And you next to her?

301
00:13:38,250 --> 00:13:38,690
Without you?

302
00:13:39,050 --> 00:13:40,450
Let's do it that way.

303
00:13:40,850 --> 00:13:43,750
And won't I end up in the middle then?

304
00:13:43,910 --> 00:13:45,710
Sis, just try to picture it.

305
00:13:45,950 --> 00:13:47,410
No, you try to picture it.

306
00:13:47,450 --> 00:13:48,710
Shut up, walrus brain.

307
00:13:49,030 --> 00:13:49,510
Lexa!

308
00:13:50,550 --> 00:13:52,840
You really should shut up, Sasa.

309
00:13:52,840 --> 00:13:53,320
Yeah.

310
00:13:54,350 --> 00:13:55,230
And go eat fish.

311
00:13:56,350 --> 00:14:07,850
What is it this time?

312
00:14:08,750 --> 00:14:12,150
Horvat got me a great jug, but I have to return it by Sunday.

313
00:14:13,050 --> 00:14:15,150
Apparently they'd notice at the Emmaus monastery.

314
00:14:16,070 --> 00:14:16,750
Can you believe that?

315
00:14:27,650 --> 00:14:28,910
This is a shambles.

316
00:14:28,910 --> 00:14:29,030
What?

317
00:14:30,250 --> 00:14:33,350
I was in line again and the tanker drove off again.

318
00:14:33,450 --> 00:14:34,470
Even though it was still full.

319
00:14:34,590 --> 00:14:35,590
Unbelievable.

320
00:14:36,350 --> 00:14:38,950
And this has happened three times already.

321
00:14:40,750 --> 00:14:42,080
French manners.

322
00:14:42,080 --> 00:14:43,060
Want something?

323
00:14:43,160 --> 00:14:44,000
Coffee, tea?

324
00:14:44,500 --> 00:14:44,940
Coffee.

325
00:14:45,450 --> 00:14:47,000
Wait, you have water?

326
00:14:47,150 --> 00:14:48,700
The whole neighborhood is dry.

327
00:14:48,700 --> 00:14:49,300
I know.

328
00:14:49,940 --> 00:14:50,380
Horvat.

329
00:14:51,810 --> 00:14:52,850
And where did he get it?

330
00:14:52,850 --> 00:14:56,630
You have to know which little valve to turn.

331
00:14:58,550 --> 00:14:59,850
That's great, I'll fill up right away.

332
00:15:01,680 --> 00:15:03,020
One liter for fifty crowns.

333
00:15:06,250 --> 00:15:07,450
That's highway robbery.

334
00:15:07,640 --> 00:15:09,960
I'd rather buy bottled water from the Vietnamese shop.

335
00:15:10,120 --> 00:15:11,020
That would offend me.

336
00:15:11,300 --> 00:15:12,400
No, they're terrible.

337
00:15:12,700 --> 00:15:14,200
I charge a kilo per bottle.

338
00:15:14,340 --> 00:15:18,460
But we Czechs and Slovaks are brothers and I wouldn't skin you alive.

339
00:15:18,840 --> 00:15:22,280
I'd rather wait for those French people to get their act together.

340
00:15:22,520 --> 00:15:23,820
I'll give you coffee at a discount.

341
00:15:24,120 --> 00:15:24,980
How much?

342
00:15:25,040 --> 00:15:25,460
Thirty.

343
00:15:26,100 --> 00:15:27,400
It used to be thirty.

344
00:15:27,480 --> 00:15:29,300
Now it's sixty, you're getting it for half price.

345
00:15:30,750 --> 00:15:31,950
These are dark times.

346
00:15:32,450 --> 00:15:33,850
When there's no water.

347
00:15:46,150 --> 00:15:47,160
It won't fit in there.

348
00:15:47,450 --> 00:15:48,450
It can be resized.

349
00:15:49,150 --> 00:15:51,250
Better not, I'd have to redo the whole thing.

350
00:15:52,750 --> 00:15:54,250
Think Ziza will like it?

351
00:15:55,410 --> 00:15:55,890
This?

352
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:01,820
She'll love it.

353
00:16:01,880 --> 00:16:02,320
Really?

354
00:16:03,050 --> 00:16:05,680
When you get married, I'll paint you one too.

355
00:16:05,680 --> 00:16:06,400
But bigger.

356
00:16:07,380 --> 00:16:08,180
Thanks, uncle.

357
00:16:08,180 --> 00:16:12,050
I hope you won't get married until after your dad lets you drink.

358
00:16:12,350 --> 00:16:13,650
I can handle kefir.

359
00:16:14,150 --> 00:16:16,250
Don't worry, I'm not getting married anytime soon.

360
00:16:17,650 --> 00:16:19,350
Let's hope Lexa can wait.

361
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:21,020
You two have been an item forever.

362
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:22,500
I'm not dating Lexa.

363
00:16:22,950 --> 00:16:24,660
Then why do you take romantic photos together?

364
00:16:24,660 --> 00:16:25,880
He showed you one?

365
00:16:26,040 --> 00:16:26,300
Yeah.

366
00:16:27,400 --> 00:16:29,200
It'd be better if you didn't take him anyway.

367
00:16:29,420 --> 00:16:30,100
That makes two of us.

368
00:16:30,400 --> 00:16:32,920
Feel free to live together casually, that's no shame these days.

369
00:16:32,980 --> 00:16:35,000
But I'd think twice about marriage.

370
00:16:35,180 --> 00:16:36,600
I've already made up my mind about that.

371
00:16:36,660 --> 00:16:37,100
Good.

372
00:16:37,300 --> 00:16:39,040
Marriage changes people for the worse.

373
00:16:39,930 --> 00:16:40,390
You think?

374
00:16:40,630 --> 00:16:41,090
Definitely.

375
00:16:41,650 --> 00:16:43,610
When we used to play "drink till you drop" in Branik.

376
00:16:43,610 --> 00:16:44,190
Drink till you drop?

377
00:16:44,750 --> 00:16:45,950
Yeah, till someone passes out.

378
00:16:46,750 --> 00:16:51,150
Metlos, Pitel, Ziza, Sicak, Bufet, Peklo and me.

379
00:16:51,230 --> 00:16:52,230
Sicak was a snake, wasn't he?

380
00:16:53,850 --> 00:16:54,850
He didn't drink either, but he hung out with us.

381
00:16:54,950 --> 00:16:58,350
Then Bufet got married and had no more time for old friends.

382
00:16:58,450 --> 00:17:00,590
His wife banned him from drinking with you?

383
00:17:00,950 --> 00:17:02,950
No, she died giving birth to quintuplets.

384
00:17:03,150 --> 00:17:04,550
He just stopped caring about us.

385
00:17:07,250 --> 00:17:09,250
I just hope Ziza handles it better.

386
00:17:09,950 --> 00:17:11,150
She's rushing it anyway.

387
00:17:11,510 --> 00:17:12,250
She's fifty now.

388
00:17:13,450 --> 00:17:15,850
She's ruining her youth.

389
00:17:19,660 --> 00:17:20,520
Where's the water?

390
00:17:20,950 --> 00:17:21,550
There isn't any.

391
00:17:21,990 --> 00:17:23,570
Tankers are nowhere and people have gone crazy.

392
00:17:23,730 --> 00:17:24,950
Water is being paid for in gold.

393
00:17:25,050 --> 00:17:26,230
Don't exaggerate.

394
00:17:26,570 --> 00:17:27,030
I'm exaggerating?

395
00:17:27,330 --> 00:17:31,210
I saw Pajerova trade her gold earrings for a case of soda.

396
00:17:31,310 --> 00:17:32,250
See how she takes care of things.

397
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:34,150
You've still got your watch on.

398
00:17:34,450 --> 00:17:35,450
So, Ivo?

399
00:17:35,950 --> 00:17:36,750
What can you do.

400
00:17:37,050 --> 00:17:39,250
I'll have to call Marcelka's salon.

401
00:17:39,450 --> 00:17:42,150
It's called Magnifique Exclusif.

402
00:17:43,250 --> 00:17:44,650
Is it French?

403
00:17:45,140 --> 00:17:45,600
Very much so.

404
00:17:46,950 --> 00:17:50,950
I'll pop over to Rohacovka Street, there's supposed to be one.

405
00:17:51,150 --> 00:17:52,450
A tanker, a new one.

406
00:17:52,950 --> 00:17:53,710
Way to go.

407
00:18:03,750 --> 00:18:04,550
What is this?

408
00:18:06,230 --> 00:18:06,790
Half a liter.

409
00:18:13,650 --> 00:18:15,150
You've had enough, off you go.

410
00:18:21,650 --> 00:18:23,830
Mom, we can't stay anymore.

411
00:18:24,150 --> 00:18:25,050
What do you mean you can't?

412
00:18:25,550 --> 00:18:28,250
We promised Uncle Horvat we'd help him with advertising.

413
00:18:28,850 --> 00:18:30,150
I need to pee.

414
00:18:30,950 --> 00:18:33,650
Go ahead, but no flushing.

415
00:18:36,350 --> 00:18:41,440
Mom, could I get my photo taken with Ivo?

416
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:42,560
Sure, why not?

417
00:18:44,750 --> 00:18:45,250
I'd also like that photo...

418
00:18:46,750 --> 00:18:47,410
I'd want one too.

419
00:18:47,530 --> 00:18:48,730
Then get one taken.

420
00:18:50,950 --> 00:18:54,350
But I'd like to have it.

421
00:18:55,070 --> 00:18:55,970
Mom doesn't have one.

422
00:18:57,850 --> 00:19:00,150
But Ivo probably wouldn't tell on you.

423
00:19:02,450 --> 00:19:04,250
Could you give me money for the photo?

424
00:19:07,110 --> 00:19:08,890
The photographer would do it for me.

425
00:19:13,950 --> 00:19:15,250
Do you want it to die?

426
00:19:20,750 --> 00:19:22,350
Mom, could I get my photo taken with Ivo?

427
00:19:25,750 --> 00:19:26,950
The pigeon, what about it?

428
00:19:29,430 --> 00:19:30,570
Fine, you can.

429
00:19:32,160 --> 00:19:32,720
Mom!

430
00:19:33,100 --> 00:19:33,460
What?

431
00:19:34,250 --> 00:19:35,550
What about me?

432
00:19:37,850 --> 00:19:39,650
Lexa definitely won't tell on you.

433
00:19:43,450 --> 00:19:44,750
Give me that key.

434
00:19:45,150 --> 00:19:46,330
I've got another one.

435
00:19:46,330 --> 00:19:47,710
I was in Rohacovka.

436
00:19:47,750 --> 00:19:48,790
Look at what won't fit in.

437
00:19:49,750 --> 00:19:50,650
The key.

438
00:19:51,050 --> 00:19:52,750
I'll stack those carp on top of each other.

439
00:20:02,650 --> 00:20:04,670
I can't stand those French people.

440
00:20:04,850 --> 00:20:07,510
They drove the tanker away right under my nose again.

441
00:20:07,850 --> 00:20:09,550
How do you know it was the French?

442
00:20:09,570 --> 00:20:11,170
I saw the driver from behind.

443
00:20:11,550 --> 00:20:12,990
He was probably Corsican.

444
00:20:13,750 --> 00:20:14,550
That's strange.

445
00:20:15,050 --> 00:20:16,320
You should call them.

446
00:20:16,550 --> 00:20:18,750
I tried, but nobody picks up.

447
00:20:18,850 --> 00:20:21,250
All you hear is Edith Piaf playing.

448
00:20:27,250 --> 00:20:28,950
You didn't drink any of it, I hope.

449
00:20:31,450 --> 00:20:32,150
Good, there's fertilizer in it.

450
00:20:35,650 --> 00:20:40,750
If you change your mind, I'll give you the number for my hair salon for Ivuska.

451
00:20:42,150 --> 00:20:44,150
You haven't given it to her yet?

452
00:20:44,170 --> 00:20:44,690
No.

453
00:20:45,450 --> 00:20:47,610
So it's not called Magnifique Exclusif?

454
00:20:47,610 --> 00:20:48,130
No.

455
00:20:49,350 --> 00:20:50,750
She made that up.

456
00:20:50,870 --> 00:20:51,930
It's called Grand Prix.

457
00:20:53,150 --> 00:20:54,550
As in "grand prize"?

458
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:56,480
More like "grand price."

459
00:20:56,950 --> 00:21:00,150
But their emergency hair service is worth the three thousand.

460
00:21:01,050 --> 00:21:02,650
Three thousand?

461
00:21:04,450 --> 00:21:05,500
I'm going to Horvat.

462
00:21:05,950 --> 00:21:08,450
I'd rather get ripped off by a Czech.

463
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:17,280
What is it?

464
00:21:20,050 --> 00:21:22,950
Ivo, if I got you the water to wash your hair, would you take a photo with me?

465
00:21:23,350 --> 00:21:25,620
I already told you, you can be in the photo.

466
00:21:25,750 --> 00:21:26,550
Next to you.

467
00:21:27,850 --> 00:21:29,950
It depends on how much water there'd be.

468
00:21:32,880 --> 00:21:33,400
No.

469
00:21:35,350 --> 00:21:35,950
Why?

470
00:21:36,350 --> 00:21:38,050
Now it's not even enough to wash my hands.

471
00:21:38,910 --> 00:21:39,610
How come?

472
00:21:39,610 --> 00:21:41,410
Now it's just enough to wash hair.

473
00:21:41,850 --> 00:21:44,150
No wonder you always wear a hat.

474
00:21:57,450 --> 00:21:58,250
Thanks, Lexa.

475
00:21:58,850 --> 00:22:00,570
There was already shampoo in it.

476
00:22:00,570 --> 00:22:01,410
Doesn't matter.

477
00:22:02,250 --> 00:22:02,890
Thanks, Dad.

478
00:22:03,250 --> 00:22:04,550
Where did you get so much water?

479
00:22:05,930 --> 00:22:07,170
Grandma's bracelet.

480
00:22:07,170 --> 00:22:09,950
I hope this will be the best photo in the world.

481
00:22:11,150 --> 00:22:14,850
I felt like I was in that fairy tale about the hen looking for water.

482
00:22:16,250 --> 00:22:18,050
Well, Mr. Pacovsky.

483
00:22:18,650 --> 00:22:19,850
What?

484
00:22:19,850 --> 00:22:25,350
But hens live in water and hunt penguins, why would they need to look for water?

485
00:22:26,450 --> 00:22:29,850
Son, when I have more strength, I'll explain a few things to you.

486
00:22:33,250 --> 00:22:34,850
Dad, this smells terribly of fish.

487
00:22:35,350 --> 00:22:35,790
Let me see.

488
00:22:39,450 --> 00:22:44,240
Well, it wouldn't fit otherwise, so Uncle Horvat poured the water on the carp.

489
00:22:44,240 --> 00:22:45,440
I'm not washing in that.

490
00:22:46,060 --> 00:22:46,940
Of course not.

491
00:22:47,560 --> 00:22:48,780
You're always making stuff up.

492
00:22:48,880 --> 00:22:50,100
I'm making stuff up?

493
00:22:50,360 --> 00:22:52,160
Dad, I'd smell like a dead fish.

494
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:54,940
Well no, actually some of those carp were still moving.

495
00:22:55,040 --> 00:22:56,760
You can't tell on the photo anyway.

496
00:22:56,840 --> 00:22:57,940
Well, that's true.

497
00:22:57,960 --> 00:22:58,480
Where are you going?

498
00:22:58,540 --> 00:22:58,960
Guess.

499
00:22:59,250 --> 00:23:00,950
Nowhere, I'm not giving you money.

500
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:02,000
You already did.

501
00:23:02,180 --> 00:23:02,460
What?

502
00:23:02,540 --> 00:23:03,600
No, no, no, hold on.

503
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:06,100
That's the food money for the whole month.

504
00:23:07,250 --> 00:23:10,650
I'll fry up some bread and we'll eat fish soup.

505
00:23:13,750 --> 00:23:14,620
Did you see that?

506
00:23:14,620 --> 00:23:15,060
What?

507
00:23:16,150 --> 00:23:18,750
No, I was looking at that walrus outside the window.

508
00:23:23,560 --> 00:23:24,380
What's going on?

509
00:23:24,380 --> 00:23:26,700
Iva just left with my money.

510
00:23:26,850 --> 00:23:28,250
I hope she didn't go get married.

511
00:23:29,150 --> 00:23:31,050
Actually, that's nonsense, Lexa's here.

512
00:23:31,850 --> 00:23:32,890
Iva wants to marry me.

513
00:23:32,890 --> 00:23:33,350
Awesome!

514
00:23:35,750 --> 00:23:37,050
She's going to the hairdresser.

515
00:23:37,550 --> 00:23:38,350
Have you seen him?

516
00:23:38,550 --> 00:23:40,150
He walks like a walrus.

517
00:23:40,450 --> 00:23:44,710
Ozzak, have you been borrowing Lexa's biology textbook by any chance?

518
00:23:44,710 --> 00:23:45,090
No.

519
00:23:46,750 --> 00:23:47,650
Strange.

520
00:23:48,050 --> 00:23:50,050
But we do talk about animals together.

521
00:23:51,010 --> 00:23:53,670
When I have more strength, I'll tell you about them too.

522
00:23:53,890 --> 00:23:54,850
Sure, go ahead.

523
00:23:54,950 --> 00:23:57,010
But it would be like carrying owls to Athens.

524
00:23:57,630 --> 00:23:58,910
Owls to Athens!

525
00:23:58,950 --> 00:24:00,250
What stinks in here?

526
00:24:00,940 --> 00:24:01,340
Water.

527
00:24:01,580 --> 00:24:02,260
I see.

528
00:24:03,050 --> 00:24:05,780
Great that you wash with it so you don't stink.

529
00:24:05,780 --> 00:24:06,460
I'm off.

530
00:24:07,050 --> 00:24:07,850
Where are you going?

531
00:24:08,750 --> 00:24:10,750
Ziza is having her bachelorette party.

532
00:24:10,850 --> 00:24:11,980
Got your name tag?

533
00:24:11,980 --> 00:24:12,660
Yeah.

534
00:24:16,030 --> 00:24:16,710
Fine.

535
00:24:30,250 --> 00:24:31,750
Aren't you overdoing it?

536
00:24:32,350 --> 00:24:33,640
As long as it's running, we're carrying.

537
00:24:34,250 --> 00:24:36,720
You can never be sure with the French.

538
00:24:37,250 --> 00:24:38,250
Not since Munich.

539
00:24:45,960 --> 00:24:46,640
Ivuska.

540
00:24:47,650 --> 00:24:50,920
I'm sure you're the prettiest in your class photo.

541
00:24:52,950 --> 00:24:53,850
But we didn't take photos.

542
00:24:54,150 --> 00:24:54,850
It rained.

543
00:24:55,250 --> 00:24:57,750
Luckily it didn't get wet, Sasa had an umbrella.

544
00:24:58,750 --> 00:25:02,640
Are you telling me you drained us financially for nothing?

545
00:25:02,950 --> 00:25:04,550
What do you mean for nothing?

546
00:25:04,950 --> 00:25:06,150
Everyone's been complimenting it.

547
00:25:07,250 --> 00:25:10,050
I already told you it looks really nice.

548
00:25:10,850 --> 00:25:11,850
Thanks, Dad.

549
00:25:15,950 --> 00:25:17,940
You're back already, it's only September.

550
00:25:18,450 --> 00:25:20,740
Well, the party ended early, but it went great.

551
00:25:20,740 --> 00:25:21,560
The wedding's off!

552
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:22,520
What?

553
00:25:22,640 --> 00:25:23,140
How come?

554
00:25:24,450 --> 00:25:25,550
Krakora showed up.

555
00:25:25,650 --> 00:25:28,550
He saw Ziza drinking beer with us.

556
00:25:28,750 --> 00:25:32,250
There was a scene, she threw her dentures at him, he picked them up and left.

557
00:25:33,850 --> 00:25:36,950
That's sad, but at least you can help me carry the water upstairs.

558
00:25:37,650 --> 00:25:38,510
No, I'm heading right out.

559
00:25:38,850 --> 00:25:39,590
Where now?

560
00:25:39,750 --> 00:25:41,550
Ziza's having her bachelorette party.

561
00:25:42,350 --> 00:25:43,150
Bye then.

562
00:25:43,340 --> 00:25:43,820
I'll be back.

563
00:25:43,820 --> 00:25:46,420
I'm not so sure, it might go on a while.

564
00:25:46,420 --> 00:25:46,900
Later.

565
00:26:25,090 --> 00:26:26,070
So, can I?

566
00:26:26,270 --> 00:26:26,750
Yeah.

567
00:26:29,150 --> 00:26:31,250
But you said there'd be three of you.

568
00:26:34,490 --> 00:26:35,590
I'm going home.

569
00:26:35,730 --> 00:26:36,190
Nowhere.

570
00:26:38,050 --> 00:26:40,750
Well, if you want that gap in there.
